<p>Nature News this week
<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120612090323/http://www.nature.com/news/2008/080312/full/452138a.html">reports</ext-link>
that</p>
<p specific-use="wrapper">
  <disp-quote>
    <p>Seven US-educated scientists working at the Max Planck Society's
    institutes are facing criminal charges for impersonating a
    doctor.</p>
  </disp-quote>
</p>
<p>This extremely embarrassing story is fortunately no longer possible.
The German Kultusministerkonferenz decided on
<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120612090323/http://www.kmk.org/aktuell/pm080306c.htm">March
6</ext-link> (text in German) to allow U.S. PhDs to call themselves Dr.
in Germany. Until this story
<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120612090323/http://blogs.wsj.com/health/2008/03/07/who-are-you-calling-doctor/">evolved</ext-link>,
I didn't even know that this is an issue.</p>
